The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, June 16: The government today deferred a decision on revising petrol and diesel prices. It is expected to take up the issue a few days later. Finance minister P. Chidambaram said the issue of raising petrol and diesel rates was on the agenda of the cabinet committee on economic affairs (CCEA). ?It has been deferred by a few days because some important ministers were not present,? he said. Public sector oil companies, which were hoping that the CCEA would discuss the crude price, were disappointed. 

 New Delhi, June 16: The finance ministry today said the economy is poised to grow 7 per cent this fiscal despite the delay in monsoon. However, it admitted that high crude prices were a matter of concern.

 New Delhi, June 16: Tata Teleservices today launched its own-brand handset, Indicom Gem, priced at Rs 1,999. Consumers would get a free truepaid connection and free talktime worth Rs 1,500 while buying the phone. The free talktime is only for local calls made to other Tata Indicom phones.

 Mumbai, June 16: Intel today said it is yet to decide on setting up the $400-million assembly test manufacturing unit in India, despite communications minister Dayanidhi Maran claiming otherwise.

 New Delhi, June 16: Nissan Motor Co today started the operations of its wholly-owned subsidiary, Nissan Motor India Pvt Ltd, based in Mumbai.

 New Delhi, June 16: Company affairs minister Prem Chand Gupta today said the government is looking into the differing views of Sebi and the Irani committee on the number of independent directors. He said, ?Quality of directors is more important than numbers.?

 New Delhi, June 16: The government has invited expression of interest from investment bankers for the divestment of part of its equity in Bharat Heavy Electricals Ltd (Bhel).




